What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 biken trips in the dataset with 16 features some of them are numeric like duration_sec and some are categories like member_gender

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out is there a relation between member gender and the duration of the trips as well as if there is a relation between the year of birth and the duration of the trips and if there is a relation between the user type and the duration of the trips

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that Member gender, member birth year, user_type and duration sec features will

# see the relation between User Type and Member Gender


counts = bike_trips.groupby(['user_type', 'member_gender']).size()
counts = counts.reset_index(name='count')
counts = counts.pivot(index = 'user_type', columns = 'member_gender', values = 'count')
sb.heatmap(counts, annot = True, fmt = 'd')
Out[125]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='member_gender', ylabel='user_type'>

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

First of all let's talk about the relationship between member birth year and the duration of trips we find that by increasing the member birth year the duration would increase, moving to the relationship between duration and Member User Type we can see that there is higher probability of having higher duration if the user of type customer and even though there are more males in both users types but females have higher duration which indicate that females tend to take more trips

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Birth year and the user type it looks like most of the users prefer the subscriber user type more than customer type the interesting thing is even they prefer the subscriber user type , users with customer type have higher durations

Conclusions¶

We start in the univariate exploration we find that males are more than females and the users with type subscriber are more than the customer type and the distribution of the duration is a positively skewed Then we moved to the bivariate exploration to support what we find in the univariate exploration and we find that most of the data points are centered in the range between 1980 and 2000 and it increases as long as we move to the right (positive) , and that females have higher duration values, Customers have higher duration than subscribers and finally males of subscriber and customer user type greater than females Finally, The multvarite exploration we find that if the gender male and user type is subscriber the duration would be the highest and if the gender is other and user type is customer the duration would be the highest, and lastly if the gender is female and user type is customer the duration would be the highest , also we found that Males and females are centered in birth year between 1980 and 2000
